WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:00:00.506 --> 00:00:10.946 A:start
[ Silence ]

00:00:11.446 --> 00:00:12.246 A:start
&gt;&gt; Good afternoon.

00:00:12.426 --> 00:00:15.286 A:start
How are you doing?

00:00:16.716 --> 00:00:22.746 A:start
Welcome to Session 301:
Extending your Apps

00:00:22.846 --> 00:00:24.606 A:start
for Enterprise and
Education Use.

00:00:25.246 --> 00:00:28.366 A:start
My name is Dave Rahardja and I'm
up here with Victor Alexander.

00:00:30.676 --> 00:00:33.576 A:start
So as you know, the use of iOS

00:00:33.576 --> 00:00:36.636 A:start
in the enterprise is
growing at a phenomenal rate.

00:00:37.526 --> 00:00:40.906 A:start
There's great momentum in the
enterprise to adopt the devices

00:00:40.906 --> 00:00:43.896 A:start
that people love so much
and that allows them to do

00:00:43.896 --> 00:00:45.616 A:start
so many things that
they couldn't do before.

00:00:47.256 --> 00:00:52.306 A:start
From everything, from retail
to corporations, to medical,

00:00:52.686 --> 00:00:56.216 A:start
to education, even
inside airline cockpits,

00:00:56.686 --> 00:00:58.466 A:start
iOS devices are everywhere
you go.

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:01:00.306 --> 00:01:03.056 A:start
A large part of the
success is of course due

00:01:03.056 --> 00:01:05.135 A:start
to the elegant design
of iOS devices,

00:01:05.776 --> 00:01:08.416 A:start
the great management
capabilities of iOS itself,

00:01:08.886 --> 00:01:12.586 A:start
data security that's built
into the device and a host,

00:01:12.586 --> 00:01:15.516 A:start
a lot of things that people
love about the device carry

00:01:15.516 --> 00:01:17.236 A:start
over into the enterprise use.

00:01:18.006 --> 00:01:22.386 A:start
But much of the success is
thanks to developers like you

00:01:23.086 --> 00:01:27.026 A:start
that develop apps that allow
the enterprise to do things

00:01:27.026 --> 00:01:27.866 A:start
that they couldn't before.

00:01:28.526 --> 00:01:31.726 A:start
Apps in the App Store,
in the custom B2B store

00:01:31.986 --> 00:01:33.536 A:start
and in-house apps
that are developed

00:01:33.536 --> 00:01:34.896 A:start
by the enterprise themselves.

00:01:36.096 --> 00:01:40.166 A:start
So during this hour,
I'd like to talk to you

00:01:40.166 --> 00:01:43.886 A:start
about how you can make
your apps more attractive

00:01:44.596 --> 00:01:46.866 A:start
to the enterprise so
you can take advantage

00:01:46.866 --> 00:01:48.666 A:start
of the growth in this industry.

00:01:49.176 --> 00:01:54.306 A:start
And I'm going to do that by
highlighting four major areas

00:01:54.636 --> 00:01:58.596 A:start
that you can implement
in your apps to do this.

00:01:59.426 --> 00:02:02.616 A:start
They are: authentication,
networking,

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:01:59.426 --> 00:02:02.616 A:start
They are: authentication,
networking,

00:02:03.736 --> 00:02:06.326 A:start
data security, and management.

00:02:07.176 --> 00:02:10.076 A:start
And, of course, this is an
incomplete list of making an app

00:02:10.076 --> 00:02:11.886 A:start
that would be attractive
to the enterprise.

00:02:12.296 --> 00:02:15.106 A:start
Of course, your apps have
to provide a solution

00:02:15.676 --> 00:02:16.526 A:start
that they're looking for.

00:02:16.746 --> 00:02:20.826 A:start
Of course, your apps have to
have a great user experience

00:02:21.486 --> 00:02:23.386 A:start
and those things are a given.

00:02:23.536 --> 00:02:25.236 A:start
But these are the things
that we're going to focus

00:02:25.236 --> 00:02:27.896 A:start
on that will let you add
that little bit of extra

00:02:28.566 --> 00:02:30.716 A:start
so that your apps stand
out from the crowd

00:02:30.716 --> 00:02:33.046 A:start
in the enterprise market.

00:02:34.696 --> 00:02:36.896 A:start
So, let's start up
with authentication.

00:02:37.826 --> 00:02:38.926 A:start
Authentication is, of course,

00:02:39.136 --> 00:02:40.476 A:start
very important in
the enterprise.

00:02:41.666 --> 00:02:46.936 A:start
When someone logs into
your app, you have to know

00:02:47.006 --> 00:02:48.906 A:start
that this person is
who they say they are.

00:02:50.316 --> 00:02:55.356 A:start
So, iOS has built an, of course,
a great authentication tool

00:02:55.356 --> 00:02:57.476 A:start
if you are an in-house developer

00:02:57.936 --> 00:02:59.276 A:start
or if you're an App
Store developer

00:02:59.276 --> 00:03:01.176 A:start
that has developed
a suite of apps

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:02:59.276 --> 00:03:01.176 A:start
that has developed
a suite of apps

00:03:01.176 --> 00:03:03.166 A:start
and we call that
shared keychain.

00:03:03.956 --> 00:03:06.556 A:start
Now, that way shared
keychain works is

00:03:06.836 --> 00:03:09.116 A:start
that if you're a developer
and you have multiple titles

00:03:09.306 --> 00:03:12.816 A:start
or multiple apps that are
deployed on a single device,

00:03:14.396 --> 00:03:18.606 A:start
those apps share the keychain
or could share the keychain.

00:03:19.636 --> 00:03:23.706 A:start
This allows you to sign into
one app and reuse the sign-in

00:03:23.706 --> 00:03:25.536 A:start
in a second app and
it's very convenient

00:03:25.536 --> 00:03:27.016 A:start
because users don't
have to keep signing

00:03:27.016 --> 00:03:28.446 A:start
in every time they
switch their apps.

00:03:29.186 --> 00:03:31.876 A:start
And for in-house developers,
this is a great solution

00:03:32.056 --> 00:03:33.836 A:start
because all your in-house
apps can be signed

00:03:33.836 --> 00:03:36.346 A:start
with the same shared
keychain with the same ID

00:03:36.776 --> 00:03:39.246 A:start
and you can implement
this in your own Apps.

00:03:40.016 --> 00:03:43.886 A:start
But what happens if you
want to mix and match?

00:03:44.536 --> 00:03:46.036 A:start
So, if you're an
enterprise and you say, "Hey,

00:03:46.036 --> 00:03:47.196 A:start
that's a great App Store app."

00:03:47.196 --> 00:03:48.316 A:start
You want to pull it in,

00:03:48.316 --> 00:03:50.356 A:start
it supports my authentication
model,

00:03:50.906 --> 00:03:53.066 A:start
but you can't really
share the keychain.

00:03:53.546 --> 00:03:56.156 A:start
So now, you end up having
to log in twice depending

00:03:56.156 --> 00:03:58.426 A:start
on which app you have.

00:03:58.626 --> 00:04:06.706 A:start
So, new in iOS 7, we are
introducing Single Sign-On.

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:03:58.626 --> 00:04:06.706 A:start
So, new in iOS 7, we are
introducing Single Sign-On.

00:04:07.206 --> 00:04:10.266 A:start
[ Applause ]

00:04:10.766 --> 00:04:14.706 A:start
Single Sign-On takes the
burden of authentication

00:04:15.686 --> 00:04:18.446 A:start
and places it inside iOS.

00:04:19.676 --> 00:04:23.946 A:start
So, let's take a
closer look at this.

00:04:24.156 --> 00:04:27.586 A:start
In iOS 7, Single Sign On is
built on top of Kerberos.

00:04:28.886 --> 00:04:30.696 A:start
This is a very popular
authentication scheme

00:04:30.696 --> 00:04:32.286 A:start
as you know inside
the enterprise.

00:04:32.666 --> 00:04:36.546 A:start
You can grant access to
your Single Sign On accounts

00:04:36.766 --> 00:04:38.426 A:start
to specific apps only.

00:04:38.426 --> 00:04:42.856 A:start
And of course, the passwords
are never stored inside the Apps

00:04:43.136 --> 00:04:44.476 A:start
but they are managed by iOS.

00:04:44.956 --> 00:04:52.766 A:start
As an app developer, this
is what you have to do.

00:04:52.766 --> 00:04:55.346 A:start
Oh and by the way, for every
one of the topics that I'm going

00:04:55.346 --> 00:04:57.336 A:start
to talk about, I'm
going to talk about it

00:04:57.336 --> 00:04:58.886 A:start
from three different
perspectives.

00:04:59.176 --> 00:05:01.696 A:start
I'm going to present to you
what iOS brings to the table.

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:04:59.176 --> 00:05:01.696 A:start
I'm going to present to you
what iOS brings to the table.

00:05:02.256 --> 00:05:04.846 A:start
And then, I'm going to talk
like I do here about what you

00:05:05.216 --> 00:05:08.436 A:start
as the app developer can do to
take advantage of the service.

00:05:08.876 --> 00:05:10.366 A:start
And then, I'm also
going to talk about it

00:05:10.366 --> 00:05:12.156 A:start
from the IT integrator's
point of view

00:05:12.716 --> 00:05:16.926 A:start
to tell you what you need
to be aware of when you want

00:05:16.996 --> 00:05:20.626 A:start
to deploy this feature in your
enterprise and what to look

00:05:20.626 --> 00:05:25.236 A:start
for when you are trying to find
the next great app to deploy

00:05:25.236 --> 00:05:26.416 A:start
in your enterprise, what kind

00:05:26.416 --> 00:05:27.566 A:start
of features you're
going to look for.

00:05:27.876 --> 00:05:28.686 A:start
So keep that in mind.

00:05:29.336 --> 00:05:30.596 A:start
So Single Sign On.

00:05:30.596 --> 00:05:34.856 A:start
As an app developer, I
have great news for you.

00:05:34.856 --> 00:05:40.516 A:start
You have no co-changes required
if you use NSURLConnection.

00:05:41.976 --> 00:05:44.056 A:start
If you don't use
NSURLConnection,

00:05:44.696 --> 00:05:46.986 A:start
the way you take advantage
of Single Sign On is

00:05:46.986 --> 00:05:48.346 A:start
to use NSURLConnection.

00:05:49.026 --> 00:05:50.946 A:start
So that's-- so we built this

00:05:50.946 --> 00:05:52.686 A:start
into the NSURLConnection
mechanism.

00:05:52.686 --> 00:05:55.966 A:start
You can also use NSURLSession
which is the great new API

00:05:55.966 --> 00:05:58.336 A:start
that we're introducing in iOS 7.

00:05:58.796 --> 00:06:02.416 A:start
So, the only change that you
will see as a developer is

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:05:58.796 --> 00:06:02.416 A:start
So, the only change that you
will see as a developer is

00:06:03.036 --> 00:06:05.986 A:start
when you access a resource
that has been configured it

00:06:05.986 --> 00:06:09.096 A:start
to be managed-- to use Single
Sign On authentication,

00:06:09.386 --> 00:06:12.556 A:start
you will not receive
this callback:

00:06:12.556 --> 00:06:15.546 A:start
the willSendRequestFor
AuthenticationChallenge

00:06:15.546 --> 00:06:16.066 A:start
callback.

00:06:16.356 --> 00:06:18.206 A:start
So, what you'll do is
you'll make a request,

00:06:18.606 --> 00:06:20.076 A:start
you will not see
an authentication,

00:06:20.346 --> 00:06:23.676 A:start
iOS will prompt the user
to enter their credentials.

00:06:24.356 --> 00:06:27.236 A:start
If it's successful, your
request will just complete,

00:06:27.236 --> 00:06:27.996 A:start
it will just succeed.

00:06:28.666 --> 00:06:31.046 A:start
If not, then it'll just fail.

00:06:32.056 --> 00:06:36.306 A:start
So, your app probably already
works with Single Sign On.

00:06:38.066 --> 00:06:42.086 A:start
For IT integrators, the way
you configure Single Sign-On is

00:06:42.086 --> 00:06:43.886 A:start
using a configuration profile.

00:06:44.176 --> 00:06:47.056 A:start
So as you know, configuration
profiles is the--

00:06:47.226 --> 00:06:50.426 A:start
is the way that we manage
settings and accounts on iOS.

00:06:51.686 --> 00:06:53.436 A:start
Inside the configuration
profile,

00:06:53.436 --> 00:06:55.736 A:start
you can define a
Single Sign-On payload,

00:06:56.506 --> 00:06:58.866 A:start
define the account,
you know, the realm.

00:06:59.616 --> 00:07:03.366 A:start
And define the app bundle IDs
that you are going to allow

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:06:59.616 --> 00:07:03.366 A:start
And define the app bundle IDs
that you are going to allow

00:07:03.366 --> 00:07:05.616 A:start
into this system, into the
Single Sign On account,

00:07:06.876 --> 00:07:09.216 A:start
you can also define
URL prefixes.

00:07:09.556 --> 00:07:12.696 A:start
So, when you go to Safari
and you hit the URL prefix,

00:07:12.696 --> 00:07:14.066 A:start
it will trigger Single Sign On.

00:07:14.576 --> 00:07:18.476 A:start
So, that's what new
in Single Sign On

00:07:18.476 --> 00:07:20.136 A:start
and authentication on iOS.

00:07:20.566 --> 00:07:25.816 A:start
Next, we're going to
talk about networking.

00:07:26.706 --> 00:07:28.066 A:start
So the networking environment

00:07:28.066 --> 00:07:31.026 A:start
in an enterprise is
maybe a little different

00:07:31.026 --> 00:07:34.436 A:start
from the environment at home.

00:07:34.436 --> 00:07:38.896 A:start
Generally, iOS has great support
for enterprise networking.

00:07:38.896 --> 00:07:43.086 A:start
It has great SSL and TLS or
TLS Support and we, of course,

00:07:43.086 --> 00:07:46.486 A:start
allow MDM to install
certificates, certificate chains

00:07:46.486 --> 00:07:47.856 A:start
and such if you have
you have your own

00:07:47.856 --> 00:07:48.926 A:start
self-signed certificates.

00:07:49.726 --> 00:07:55.616 A:start
Then, we also have proxy support
both per SSID and Global Proxy,

00:07:56.086 --> 00:08:01.636 A:start
and we support enterprise
Wi-Fi 802.1X, WPA, WPA2,

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:07:56.086 --> 00:08:01.636 A:start
and we support enterprise
Wi-Fi 802.1X, WPA, WPA2,

00:08:02.096 --> 00:08:04.566 A:start
and we support virtual
private networks.

00:08:04.946 --> 00:08:09.526 A:start
And VPN tunnels the
traffic from your iOS device

00:08:09.526 --> 00:08:12.116 A:start
into the enterprise,
into the intranet.

00:08:12.576 --> 00:08:15.196 A:start
All right, something
new in iOS 7,

00:08:15.996 --> 00:08:17.936 A:start
we're introducing per-app VPN.

00:08:19.416 --> 00:08:19.956 A:start
So, what's this?

00:08:21.306 --> 00:08:23.296 A:start
Here is what this conceptual--

00:08:23.296 --> 00:08:28.286 A:start
a conceptual model of
what per-app VPN does.

00:08:28.476 --> 00:08:29.686 A:start
So, let's say you have two apps

00:08:29.686 --> 00:08:32.476 A:start
that the enterprise has
installed: app one and two,

00:08:33.356 --> 00:08:35.326 A:start
and you have an app
that the user installed

00:08:35.326 --> 00:08:36.326 A:start
on their own device.

00:08:36.326 --> 00:08:38.145 A:start
Let's say this is a "bring
your own device" scenario,

00:08:38.145 --> 00:08:39.556 A:start
the user installs
their own device--

00:08:39.736 --> 00:08:41.135 A:start
their own app on the App Store.

00:08:42.056 --> 00:08:47.056 A:start
Per-app VPN allows you to
specify that apps one and two go

00:08:47.056 --> 00:08:51.466 A:start
to the VPN into the corporate
intranet and not app three.

00:08:51.576 --> 00:08:54.076 A:start
App three that the user
installed does not get access

00:08:54.076 --> 00:08:54.726 A:start
to the intranet.

00:08:55.666 --> 00:08:57.096 A:start
So that's what it
is conceptually.

00:08:58.396 --> 00:09:01.776 A:start
This limits VPN access
to only the apps

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:08:58.396 --> 00:09:01.776 A:start
This limits VPN access
to only the apps

00:09:01.776 --> 00:09:04.536 A:start
that the enterprise has
installed, specific Apps.

00:09:05.346 --> 00:09:09.406 A:start
It enhances both
security and privacy.

00:09:09.746 --> 00:09:14.796 A:start
So, security because you are not
exposing your intranet to apps

00:09:14.886 --> 00:09:17.696 A:start
that the user may have installed
from the App Store on their own.

00:09:17.976 --> 00:09:21.706 A:start
That's better than
system wide VPN.

00:09:22.686 --> 00:09:26.906 A:start
And privacy, because your
user's personal traffic

00:09:26.976 --> 00:09:28.316 A:start
to the internet does not go

00:09:28.316 --> 00:09:32.626 A:start
through your enterprise
network, all right?

00:09:38.526 --> 00:09:40.236 A:start
I knew you'd like that.

00:09:40.666 --> 00:09:44.496 A:start
All right, so per-app VPN for
app developers, what do you have

00:09:44.496 --> 00:09:46.656 A:start
to do to take advantage
of this great feature?

00:09:47.686 --> 00:09:50.566 A:start
Nothing, your app already works.

00:09:51.246 --> 00:09:53.586 A:start
It works transparently, you
don't have to change a thing,

00:09:53.796 --> 00:09:56.166 A:start
this is my favorite
slide, it's great.

00:09:58.116 --> 00:10:01.596 A:start
For IT integrators, what do you
have to do to install this--

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:09:58.116 --> 00:10:01.596 A:start
For IT integrators, what do you
have to do to install this--

00:10:01.596 --> 00:10:03.686 A:start
to configure this feature?

00:10:04.196 --> 00:10:07.646 A:start
You need support from
your VPN plug-in.

00:10:07.646 --> 00:10:09.326 A:start
Now, these are the
same VPN plug-ins

00:10:09.326 --> 00:10:10.756 A:start
that you probably already use

00:10:10.806 --> 00:10:13.156 A:start
from your third party
VPN vendors.

00:10:13.706 --> 00:10:14.756 A:start
They need to have a plug-in

00:10:14.756 --> 00:10:20.336 A:start
that supports the
notion of per-app VPN.

00:10:20.546 --> 00:10:22.096 A:start
Once that plug-in is installed,

00:10:22.476 --> 00:10:24.626 A:start
you then configure
the VPN account

00:10:25.026 --> 00:10:29.516 A:start
with a configuration profile
through MDM and then you use MDM

00:10:29.516 --> 00:10:33.986 A:start
to tag which apps are allowed
to use that VPN connection.

00:10:34.716 --> 00:10:35.966 A:start
More things about networking?

00:10:36.486 --> 00:10:40.416 A:start
If you are developing
without using NSURLConnection,

00:10:40.726 --> 00:10:41.916 A:start
you'll see a pattern
here by the way.

00:10:42.496 --> 00:10:47.686 A:start
If you don't use NSURLConnection
or NSUrlSession, you must--

00:10:47.756 --> 00:10:50.816 A:start
you need to be aware
of the presence

00:10:50.816 --> 00:10:52.846 A:start
of proxies inside
the enterprise.

00:10:53.766 --> 00:10:57.186 A:start
If you are using NSURLConnection
or the new NSURLSession,

00:10:57.396 --> 00:10:58.846 A:start
we take care of that
for you, you have to--

00:10:58.896 --> 00:10:59.916 A:start
don't have to worry about it.

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:11:00.536 --> 00:11:03.026 A:start
But if you're using
say, CFSocketStream

00:11:03.026 --> 00:11:06.226 A:start
or UNIX level sockets, you
need to be aware of that.

00:11:06.226 --> 00:11:08.966 A:start
Read the API, you probably need
to move some data structures

00:11:08.966 --> 00:11:10.906 A:start
around to take care
of the presence

00:11:10.906 --> 00:11:14.246 A:start
of proxies in your path.

00:11:14.246 --> 00:11:16.906 A:start
And as a final note and this
is not just for enterprise,

00:11:16.906 --> 00:11:19.046 A:start
this is just good practice
for an app developer.

00:11:19.916 --> 00:11:23.496 A:start
Be conscious of your
app's cellular data usage.

00:11:24.436 --> 00:11:28.286 A:start
In iOS 7, we've enhanced
multi-tasking

00:11:28.766 --> 00:11:32.716 A:start
so that your app can be woken
up at particular intervals

00:11:32.716 --> 00:11:34.326 A:start
or when a push notification
comes in.

00:11:35.096 --> 00:11:37.716 A:start
This is great for you to
update the status of your app

00:11:38.486 --> 00:11:39.956 A:start
but you need to ask
the question,

00:11:40.256 --> 00:11:41.966 A:start
"Should I be doing
this over cellular?"

00:11:42.196 --> 00:11:45.366 A:start
If you're going to update
a large amount of data,

00:11:45.916 --> 00:11:48.096 A:start
maybe you should defer it to
when the user brings the app

00:11:48.096 --> 00:11:51.116 A:start
to UI foreground or
when you are in Wi-Fi.

00:11:51.426 --> 00:11:55.486 A:start
So, in an enterprise, it
is especially attractive

00:11:55.656 --> 00:11:58.126 A:start
if your app knows
how to behave itself

00:11:58.126 --> 00:12:00.246 A:start
and limit the consumption
of cellular data.

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:11:58.126 --> 00:12:00.246 A:start
and limit the consumption
of cellular data.

00:12:01.236 --> 00:12:05.026 A:start
And the way you do that is
you tag your URL request

00:12:05.286 --> 00:12:09.666 A:start
with this property,
allowsCellularAccess equals no

00:12:09.936 --> 00:12:13.686 A:start
and that-- really, that's it
and that request will not go

00:12:13.686 --> 00:12:16.016 A:start
out over cellular, very simple.

00:12:16.536 --> 00:12:20.846 A:start
So, that's a short session on
networking in the enterprise.

00:12:21.436 --> 00:12:25.216 A:start
Next stop, data security.

00:12:29.536 --> 00:12:32.906 A:start
So, data security is very
important in the enterprise.

00:12:34.416 --> 00:12:37.016 A:start
One of the things that you'll
notice when you develop apps

00:12:37.016 --> 00:12:39.546 A:start
for the enterprise is
the enterprise is really,

00:12:39.546 --> 00:12:41.266 A:start
really concerned
about the security

00:12:41.266 --> 00:12:42.646 A:start
and privacy of their data.

00:12:43.546 --> 00:12:46.306 A:start
And here are some
things that are available

00:12:46.306 --> 00:12:47.466 A:start
to you in iOS already.

00:12:48.166 --> 00:12:52.886 A:start
So, built into iOS, we have a
great data protection model.

00:12:54.786 --> 00:12:57.416 A:start
There are three main
data protection classes

00:12:57.416 --> 00:12:59.986 A:start
in iOS, just to review.

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:13:01.016 --> 00:13:03.486 A:start
There are some subtle variations
on these, but basically,

00:13:03.486 --> 00:13:05.756 A:start
there are three classes
that you can choose from.

00:13:06.176 --> 00:13:09.776 A:start
These classes can be applied to
files that you write to flash.

00:13:10.316 --> 00:13:13.866 A:start
So you have none which is none,
they're not data protected.

00:13:14.886 --> 00:13:17.396 A:start
You have complete
with authentication

00:13:18.276 --> 00:13:21.876 A:start
which protects the data
in an encrypted fashion

00:13:21.916 --> 00:13:24.516 A:start
until the user enters
their passcode

00:13:24.516 --> 00:13:26.046 A:start
for the first time
after a restart.

00:13:26.876 --> 00:13:31.756 A:start
And complete, which will
protect your data as long

00:13:31.756 --> 00:13:32.696 A:start
as the phone is locked.

00:13:32.896 --> 00:13:35.636 A:start
So when the user locks the
phone again, it gets protected.

00:13:35.716 --> 00:13:36.736 A:start
Let me illustrate that.

00:13:36.736 --> 00:13:41.806 A:start
So, after the device has
restarted, none is readable,

00:13:41.896 --> 00:13:44.336 A:start
the others are encrypted,
unreadable by your apps.

00:13:44.756 --> 00:13:48.306 A:start
When the user enters
their passcode,

00:13:48.816 --> 00:13:51.056 A:start
then all the classes
become available

00:13:51.056 --> 00:13:51.996 A:start
for reading and writing.

00:13:51.996 --> 00:13:56.266 A:start
When the user locks
the device again,

00:13:56.816 --> 00:13:59.966 A:start
that complete class gets
locked while the others

00:13:59.966 --> 00:14:00.996 A:start
remain unencrypted.

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:13:59.966 --> 00:14:00.996 A:start
remain unencrypted.

00:14:01.356 --> 00:14:04.996 A:start
So, keep that in mind, this is
the model that you can choose

00:14:04.996 --> 00:14:09.646 A:start
from and you can start to
see that this is a good way

00:14:09.646 --> 00:14:12.236 A:start
of binning your data
to see which kind

00:14:12.236 --> 00:14:14.636 A:start
of sensitivity does
the enterprise have

00:14:14.636 --> 00:14:17.726 A:start
about that particular
file and for you to choose

00:14:18.216 --> 00:14:21.306 A:start
which class you want
to choose from.

00:14:21.896 --> 00:14:25.176 A:start
So, but there's one
thing new in iOS 7

00:14:25.876 --> 00:14:27.466 A:start
that we're really proud of.

00:14:27.736 --> 00:14:32.676 A:start
We are improving the data
security of all apps in iOS 7

00:14:32.676 --> 00:14:35.116 A:start
across the board,
even App Store apps.

00:14:36.056 --> 00:14:38.636 A:start
All App Store apps
and enterprise apps

00:14:38.666 --> 00:14:42.326 A:start
that are installed in iOS
7 automatically receive the

00:14:42.826 --> 00:14:45.656 A:start
complete until first
authentication class,

00:14:45.656 --> 00:14:46.596 A:start
the second class.

00:14:47.246 --> 00:14:49.276 A:start
What this means is that
for the enterprise,

00:14:49.276 --> 00:14:51.106 A:start
for the IT integrators
of the enterprise,

00:14:51.576 --> 00:14:53.996 A:start
you can now feel confident
that when you install an app

00:14:53.996 --> 00:14:57.236 A:start
from the App Store even,
that that data has some--

00:14:57.236 --> 00:14:59.056 A:start
has a greater level
of protection

00:14:59.056 --> 00:15:01.546 A:start
in iOS 7 than it did in iOS 6.

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:14:59.056 --> 00:15:01.546 A:start
in iOS 7 than it did in iOS 6.

00:15:01.686 --> 00:15:03.056 A:start
And we do this across the board

00:15:03.276 --> 00:15:07.376 A:start
and there's no change
required for most of the apps.

00:15:07.456 --> 00:15:11.846 A:start
Also, you may be aware or
not that starting from iOS 6,

00:15:12.066 --> 00:15:15.196 A:start
we have FIPS 140-2
certification.

00:15:15.746 --> 00:15:17.406 A:start
This is a government
certification

00:15:17.736 --> 00:15:21.046 A:start
that certifies the
integrity of our crypto,

00:15:21.046 --> 00:15:24.976 A:start
CoreCrypto algorithms and
we're really proud of this.

00:15:25.176 --> 00:15:29.516 A:start
So, for app developers,
what do you have to--

00:15:30.136 --> 00:15:32.226 A:start
what can you do to
enhance your data security?

00:15:33.016 --> 00:15:37.186 A:start
Well, use the protection
complete class when appropriate.

00:15:37.896 --> 00:15:41.276 A:start
Ask yourself the question,
if somebody were to be able

00:15:41.276 --> 00:15:42.796 A:start
to read this file off a disk--

00:15:42.796 --> 00:15:47.746 A:start
off the disk, will that make
my enterprise customer happy

00:15:47.746 --> 00:15:48.106 A:start
or not?

00:15:48.846 --> 00:15:50.996 A:start
And if the answer is no,

00:15:50.996 --> 00:15:54.466 A:start
then please consider using the
File Protection Complete Class.

00:15:56.356 --> 00:15:59.866 A:start
There is a small wrinkle
when you do that, of course,

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:16:00.166 --> 00:16:02.916 A:start
when the device is locked
and your App gets woken

00:16:02.916 --> 00:16:06.506 A:start
up by multi-tasking, you can't
actually write to your database

00:16:06.506 --> 00:16:08.566 A:start
because it's unreadable
and unwritable.

00:16:08.566 --> 00:16:11.986 A:start
And as I said, there are
some variations to this theme

00:16:11.986 --> 00:16:15.626 A:start
but in general you will be woken
up and then you'll discover

00:16:15.626 --> 00:16:18.186 A:start
that you can't write to the
files that you need to write.

00:16:19.066 --> 00:16:23.196 A:start
So, at this time, consider
what your options are.

00:16:23.546 --> 00:16:28.336 A:start
First of all, you can always
write down the fact or write

00:16:28.336 --> 00:16:30.526 A:start
to disk the fact that
there is an update

00:16:31.096 --> 00:16:32.796 A:start
and the next time the
user launches the app

00:16:32.796 --> 00:16:37.016 A:start
in UI foreground, device is
unlocked, go fetch the update.

00:16:37.136 --> 00:16:39.896 A:start
Or you can create
a side buffer file

00:16:40.316 --> 00:16:42.386 A:start
of maybe the second
protection class, you know,

00:16:42.386 --> 00:16:44.336 A:start
complete until first
user authentication

00:16:44.656 --> 00:16:47.246 A:start
to buffer your data.

00:16:47.336 --> 00:16:50.306 A:start
And then, write that over
to the protected data base

00:16:50.306 --> 00:16:51.806 A:start
when your App goes
to foreground.

00:16:52.036 --> 00:16:53.796 A:start
But of course, the
question you ask there is,

00:16:53.976 --> 00:16:55.726 A:start
should I be doing
that with this data?

00:16:56.206 --> 00:16:58.416 A:start
And if the answer is no,
then just write the fact

00:16:58.416 --> 00:17:00.796 A:start
that you are-- that you
need to do an update

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:16:58.416 --> 00:17:00.796 A:start
that you are-- that you
need to do an update

00:17:00.796 --> 00:17:03.066 A:start
when the app comes back
to foreground and do it

00:17:03.066 --> 00:17:04.665 A:start
when the app starts back up.

00:17:06.296 --> 00:17:10.076 A:start
The keychain has an additional
attribute that you can place

00:17:10.076 --> 00:17:12.396 A:start
on the data security
of each item.

00:17:13.026 --> 00:17:14.056 A:start
You can assign an app--

00:17:14.056 --> 00:17:16.596 A:start
a data security attribute
per keychain item by the way,

00:17:16.675 --> 00:17:18.056 A:start
the same classes that
you have up there

00:17:18.596 --> 00:17:21.226 A:start
with an additional
feature in there.

00:17:21.776 --> 00:17:24.846 A:start
If you'll notice, the
attribute here says accessible

00:17:24.846 --> 00:17:28.406 A:start
after first unlock this
device only in the end.

00:17:29.356 --> 00:17:33.066 A:start
This helps you to secure
credentials, private keys,

00:17:33.066 --> 00:17:36.956 A:start
passwords or whatever from
getting backed up off the device

00:17:37.226 --> 00:17:38.896 A:start
and restored to another device.

00:17:39.736 --> 00:17:42.366 A:start
Right? The fact that your
keychain items are backed up

00:17:42.366 --> 00:17:45.386 A:start
and restored as a great
convenience for end-users

00:17:45.616 --> 00:17:47.326 A:start
because you don't
have to log in again.

00:17:47.666 --> 00:17:50.606 A:start
But for the enterprise, you
should ask the question,

00:17:51.116 --> 00:17:53.856 A:start
if a user logs into this
device which may be managed

00:17:53.856 --> 00:17:57.126 A:start
by the enterprise, is it
appropriate for that login

00:17:57.126 --> 00:17:59.876 A:start
to transfer to another
device that the user owns

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:18:00.326 --> 00:18:02.246 A:start
that may not be managed, right?

00:18:02.726 --> 00:18:05.686 A:start
So in many cases, the
answer is no, and you need

00:18:05.686 --> 00:18:10.456 A:start
to put this attribute on the
keychain items to prevent backup

00:18:10.456 --> 00:18:13.476 A:start
and restore from taking that
credential out of that device.

00:18:13.966 --> 00:18:18.586 A:start
And finally, iCloud
Document Sync.

00:18:19.416 --> 00:18:22.406 A:start
Now, iCloud Document Sync is
another feature that users love

00:18:23.506 --> 00:18:28.106 A:start
but this becomes a
problem for enterprise data

00:18:28.576 --> 00:18:32.226 A:start
because sensitive enterprise
data may leak out into the cloud

00:18:32.226 --> 00:18:34.886 A:start
and into other unmanaged
and unprotected devices.

00:18:35.936 --> 00:18:38.166 A:start
So, the enterprise
does have a restriction

00:18:38.486 --> 00:18:41.816 A:start
to disable iCloud document
sync across the whole device.

00:18:42.566 --> 00:18:46.886 A:start
And it would be better
if there was a way

00:18:46.886 --> 00:18:49.926 A:start
to disable iCloud Document
sync in your app only

00:18:49.926 --> 00:18:51.136 A:start
so that the user doesn't have

00:18:51.166 --> 00:18:52.946 A:start
to turn off document
sync across the board.

00:18:53.726 --> 00:18:56.076 A:start
So, consider adding a--

00:18:56.076 --> 00:18:58.656 A:start
the capability of
storing your documents

00:18:58.656 --> 00:19:00.856 A:start
in your local documents
folder instead

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:18:58.656 --> 00:19:00.856 A:start
in your local documents
folder instead

00:19:00.856 --> 00:19:02.416 A:start
of the iCloud document folder

00:19:02.746 --> 00:19:05.146 A:start
when your app is configured
for enterprise use.

00:19:05.966 --> 00:19:08.286 A:start
But, how do you configure
your app for enterprise use?

00:19:08.286 --> 00:19:10.476 A:start
You certainly don't
want to put a UI switch

00:19:10.846 --> 00:19:12.536 A:start
to let users turn
off this feature.

00:19:13.476 --> 00:19:15.636 A:start
Well, there's a great way
of doing that and I'll talk

00:19:15.636 --> 00:19:17.766 A:start
about it a few slides
down so hang in there.

00:19:20.086 --> 00:19:22.036 A:start
So, there's data security.

00:19:22.536 --> 00:19:26.236 A:start
Let's talk about management.

00:19:27.656 --> 00:19:31.376 A:start
When we talk about management
on iOS, we generally talk

00:19:31.376 --> 00:19:34.106 A:start
about mobile device
management protocol.

00:19:34.836 --> 00:19:38.606 A:start
This is a very powerful protocol
that allows an enterprise

00:19:38.916 --> 00:19:41.656 A:start
to manage and administer
thousands

00:19:41.656 --> 00:19:44.126 A:start
of iOS devices over the air.

00:19:45.346 --> 00:19:50.036 A:start
And some of the things MDM
can do, it can set passcode

00:19:50.236 --> 00:19:52.846 A:start
and security policies,
like you'd have

00:19:52.846 --> 00:19:54.936 A:start
to have a certain
number of letters

00:19:54.936 --> 00:19:56.606 A:start
in your passcode
and stuff like that.

00:19:57.436 --> 00:20:03.426 A:start
It can install accounts
including email, calendar, VPN,

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:19:57.436 --> 00:20:03.426 A:start
It can install accounts
including email, calendar, VPN,

00:20:03.426 --> 00:20:06.776 A:start
you know, Wi-Fi accounts,
any-- all kinds of accounts.

00:20:07.866 --> 00:20:12.756 A:start
It can remotely erase your
device and it can, of course,

00:20:13.046 --> 00:20:19.396 A:start
great news for you, install
and remove apps over the air.

00:20:19.396 --> 00:20:23.156 A:start
Now, the accounts and
apps that are installed

00:20:23.156 --> 00:20:26.836 A:start
by MDM are called Managed
Apps, Accounts and Apps.

00:20:27.346 --> 00:20:29.736 A:start
So things that are
installed with MDM are Managed

00:20:30.346 --> 00:20:32.966 A:start
and the things that
users install

00:20:32.966 --> 00:20:34.336 A:start
in the device are
called Unmanaged.

00:20:35.736 --> 00:20:39.246 A:start
So, Managed Apps and Accounts.

00:20:40.046 --> 00:20:45.516 A:start
So in iOS 7, we're
introducing another great way

00:20:45.516 --> 00:20:48.566 A:start
to manage the data inside your
managed apps and accounts,

00:20:48.926 --> 00:20:51.156 A:start
we call it Managed Open In.

00:20:52.216 --> 00:20:55.796 A:start
Managed Open In prevents the
unintentional data movement

00:20:56.546 --> 00:21:00.246 A:start
between managed and
unmanaged apps and accounts.

