00:23:31.986 --> 00:23:34.066 A:start
Next up, a great new feature

00:23:34.066 --> 00:23:37.246 A:start
in iOS 7 called App
Configuration and Feedback.

00:23:38.576 --> 00:23:39.826 A:start
So, what is this?

00:23:40.976 --> 00:23:45.166 A:start
This is a way to reduce your
support calls, IT integrators,

00:23:46.226 --> 00:23:48.286 A:start
by configuring apps
that you install.

00:23:48.546 --> 00:23:54.426 A:start
And the way to do this is an
MDM server can send a dictionary

00:23:54.796 --> 00:23:57.626 A:start
into a managed app
to configure it.

00:23:58.266 --> 00:24:02.016 A:start
Now, the dictionary that
you push down appears

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:23:58.266 --> 00:24:02.016 A:start
Now, the dictionary that
you push down appears

00:24:02.166 --> 00:24:05.816 A:start
in the NSUserDefaults of that
app, it's very convenient.

00:24:07.246 --> 00:24:11.016 A:start
And the feedback part of this
allows an app to write something

00:24:11.016 --> 00:24:16.006 A:start
into the NSUserDefaults that
can be read by the MDM Server

00:24:16.006 --> 00:24:20.496 A:start
to report-- to report back
a status out of band, right?

00:24:21.726 --> 00:24:22.766 A:start
It's very simple.

00:24:22.766 --> 00:24:25.076 A:start
As an app developer here's--
here is all you need now.

00:24:25.436 --> 00:24:28.216 A:start
This is very similar
to what happens

00:24:28.216 --> 00:24:29.386 A:start
if you use a settings bundle.

00:24:29.476 --> 00:24:31.466 A:start
So, if you already
have a settings bundle

00:24:31.626 --> 00:24:34.886 A:start
that allows the user
to go to Settings

00:24:34.886 --> 00:24:37.356 A:start
and configure your apps, this
is very, very similar to that.

00:24:37.706 --> 00:24:38.386 A:start
Excuse me.

00:24:39.386 --> 00:24:42.136 A:start
Your app needs to
read the dictionary

00:24:42.136 --> 00:24:48.536 A:start
from a particular magic key:
com.apple.configuration.managed,

00:24:48.586 --> 00:24:51.446 A:start
that's where the dictionary
will appear that's pushed

00:24:51.446 --> 00:24:52.506 A:start
down by the enterprise.

00:24:53.896 --> 00:24:57.606 A:start
When you write your feedback
out, write it to com--

00:24:57.906 --> 00:25:02.336 A:start
NSUserDefaults key
com.apple.feedback.managed.

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:24:57.906 --> 00:25:02.336 A:start
NSUserDefaults key
com.apple.feedback.managed.

00:25:02.716 --> 00:25:05.216 A:start
And when the MDM
Server queries your app,

00:25:05.216 --> 00:25:07.126 A:start
it will find your
dictionary there.

00:25:08.506 --> 00:25:11.846 A:start
Listen to this notification, the
defaults did change notification

00:25:12.406 --> 00:25:15.576 A:start
to be aware that the
configuration has changed

00:25:15.856 --> 00:25:17.536 A:start
or that the server
has read your feedback

00:25:17.536 --> 00:25:19.036 A:start
and erased it to make it nil.

00:25:19.686 --> 00:25:21.606 A:start
You can be aware of that
by listening to this.

00:25:21.956 --> 00:25:25.296 A:start
And your app may not be
running, of course, when you--

00:25:25.296 --> 00:25:26.696 A:start
when the configuration changes

00:25:26.696 --> 00:25:28.466 A:start
or when the feedback
is retrieved and erased

00:25:28.466 --> 00:25:29.926 A:start
from your NSUserDefaults.

00:25:30.376 --> 00:25:33.856 A:start
So, read the configuration
every time your app starts up.

00:25:34.106 --> 00:25:36.506 A:start
Again, the same things
that you've already done

00:25:36.506 --> 00:25:39.166 A:start
for Settings bundles,
basically, the same idea.

00:25:40.086 --> 00:25:42.356 A:start
So, in order to show
you how this works,

00:25:42.356 --> 00:25:44.996 A:start
I'm going to ask Victor
to come back up here

00:25:44.996 --> 00:25:47.466 A:start
to give you a little demo.

00:25:48.416 --> 00:25:49.236 A:start
&gt;&gt; Thanks Dave.

00:25:52.376 --> 00:25:54.196 A:start
So here, we have a
sample application

00:25:54.196 --> 00:25:56.486 A:start
that was developed using app
configuration and feedback

00:25:56.926 --> 00:25:59.306 A:start
and you'll notice at the top
here, we've got a URL bar,

00:25:59.306 --> 00:26:02.226 A:start
we've got a success and failure
values that were tracking.

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:25:59.306 --> 00:26:02.226 A:start
we've got a success and failure
values that were tracking.

00:26:02.466 --> 00:26:04.446 A:start
And in the center,
we've got a UIWebView.

00:26:04.806 --> 00:26:06.106 A:start
And also at the bottom
here, take note,

00:26:06.106 --> 00:26:08.056 A:start
we have a Cloud document
sync switch.

00:26:08.256 --> 00:26:09.716 A:start
Maybe not something you
might want to add to the UI

00:26:09.716 --> 00:26:12.436 A:start
of your app but for the
purposes of our sample demo,

00:26:12.436 --> 00:26:13.856 A:start
I think it's appropriate to use.

00:26:15.046 --> 00:26:16.986 A:start
So, you might notice at
the top of the application,

00:26:17.126 --> 00:26:20.166 A:start
we have URL that might
not work correctly.

00:26:20.516 --> 00:26:23.346 A:start
Let's start tap the go button
here and see what happens.

00:26:24.186 --> 00:26:25.616 A:start
Our app is not quite
working correctly,

00:26:25.616 --> 00:26:27.976 A:start
we got a failure
there, no web page loads

00:26:27.976 --> 00:26:29.496 A:start
in the center, we've
got a problem.

00:26:29.496 --> 00:26:31.796 A:start
This might be something
your user hits if they want

00:26:32.116 --> 00:26:34.736 A:start
to load their login information
for their enterprise app

00:26:34.736 --> 00:26:37.496 A:start
or help documentation and
if we try and connect,

00:26:38.286 --> 00:26:39.346 A:start
we just keep hitting errors.

00:26:39.816 --> 00:26:41.526 A:start
Wouldn't it be nice
if we had a mechanism

00:26:41.706 --> 00:26:44.386 A:start
through which we could update
that, reset it, correct it

00:26:44.386 --> 00:26:47.716 A:start
and get this app back
into a working state?

00:26:48.476 --> 00:26:51.586 A:start
So since the URL
value is something

00:26:51.756 --> 00:26:54.756 A:start
that I configured using app
configuration, I could push

00:26:54.756 --> 00:26:58.546 A:start
down the change to that app
to update the URL and see

00:26:58.546 --> 00:26:59.496 A:start
if we can get things working.

00:26:59.496 --> 00:27:02.016 A:start
So, I'm going to go ahead
and push down that change,

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:26:59.496 --> 00:27:02.016 A:start
So, I'm going to go ahead
and push down that change,

00:27:02.846 --> 00:27:05.066 A:start
give it a moment for the
device to receive it.

00:27:05.346 --> 00:27:07.786 A:start
You noticed almost immediately,
the URL bar updates,

00:27:08.216 --> 00:27:11.416 A:start
you noticed almost immediately
the URL string updates

00:27:11.416 --> 00:27:14.336 A:start
with a much more valid
looking URL and also note

00:27:14.336 --> 00:27:16.106 A:start
that the UI Switch
is now disabled.

00:27:16.106 --> 00:27:18.246 A:start
So, we've done a couple of
really powerful things here

00:27:18.246 --> 00:27:20.616 A:start
to get this app into a
better state and let's see

00:27:20.616 --> 00:27:25.096 A:start
as a test here, I will tap,
go and our webpage loads

00:27:25.096 --> 00:27:27.636 A:start
in the UIWebView as expected
which is-- which is excellent.

00:27:28.136 --> 00:27:30.596 A:start
Now, we have these-- so
that's the configuration side

00:27:30.596 --> 00:27:32.976 A:start
of things, what about the
feedback side of things?

00:27:33.066 --> 00:27:35.356 A:start
We've hit, you know,
three errors on this app.

00:27:35.586 --> 00:27:37.526 A:start
It might be useful for the
enterprise to find that out

00:27:37.686 --> 00:27:40.926 A:start
if users are having problems or
issues and we can have the MDM

00:27:40.926 --> 00:27:46.056 A:start
to sort of pull that information
from the apps and collect it

00:27:46.056 --> 00:27:47.686 A:start
and work with that data.

00:27:48.056 --> 00:27:52.286 A:start
Now, if I place a command to
this app from the MDM Server

00:27:52.946 --> 00:27:55.346 A:start
to fetch that error information.

00:27:55.546 --> 00:27:58.086 A:start
What we'll see here is
that not only the failures

00:27:58.086 --> 00:28:01.136 A:start
but the success values
were pulled out of the app,

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:27:58.086 --> 00:28:01.136 A:start
but the success values
were pulled out of the app,

00:28:01.136 --> 00:28:04.046 A:start
sent back to the MDM Server
for evaluation by the IT Staff.

00:28:04.046 --> 00:28:06.596 A:start
But also, the values
were set back to zero

00:28:06.796 --> 00:28:10.446 A:start
so that any future polls for
that information can be clean

00:28:10.446 --> 00:28:11.736 A:start
and updated and evaluated

00:28:11.736 --> 00:28:13.726 A:start
between the last two times
the information was pulled.

00:28:14.116 --> 00:28:16.046 A:start
And that is app configuration
and feedback.

00:28:16.426 --> 00:28:17.326 A:start
Back to you Dave.

00:28:17.786 --> 00:28:18.516 A:start
&gt;&gt; Thank you Victor.

00:28:22.666 --> 00:28:24.936 A:start
So app configuration
and feedback,

00:28:25.116 --> 00:28:28.166 A:start
very simple feature,
very powerful.

00:28:28.986 --> 00:28:32.386 A:start
For IT integrators,
this is invaluable

00:28:32.386 --> 00:28:35.306 A:start
to configure the apps
in your enterprise.

00:28:35.566 --> 00:28:37.536 A:start
You need to look for
apps that support this.

00:28:38.056 --> 00:28:40.266 A:start
Now normally, you would
send out apps to your users

00:28:40.266 --> 00:28:42.486 A:start
and then send them a email
or something that says, "Hey,

00:28:42.486 --> 00:28:44.646 A:start
tap this, tap that,
type this in, type that"

00:28:44.646 --> 00:28:48.136 A:start
and you get you know--
and you get support calls.

00:28:48.786 --> 00:28:52.516 A:start
With app configuration, you
can prepare the dictionary

00:28:52.966 --> 00:28:55.426 A:start
for that app and
send it to the users

00:28:55.426 --> 00:28:56.576 A:start
without their intervention.

00:28:56.876 --> 00:28:59.296 A:start
The first time they launch that
app, it's already configured.

00:28:59.766 --> 00:29:03.846 A:start
Let's take a closer look at
what's going on under the--

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:28:59.766 --> 00:29:03.846 A:start
Let's take a closer look at
what's going on under the--

00:29:03.846 --> 00:29:04.606 A:start
under the covers here.

00:29:05.176 --> 00:29:12.626 A:start
So, I added this notification
observer in viewDidLoad.

00:29:12.626 --> 00:29:16.576 A:start
You could add this view
will appear or, you know,

00:29:16.576 --> 00:29:18.546 A:start
in your apps delegate or
wherever it's appropriate

00:29:18.546 --> 00:29:19.866 A:start
for you handle the event.

00:29:20.706 --> 00:29:24.256 A:start
So, the first thing you
notice is I added an observer

00:29:24.256 --> 00:29:26.416 A:start
for NSUseDefaultsDidChange,

00:29:27.116 --> 00:29:30.346 A:start
always add the notification
observer before reading the

00:29:30.346 --> 00:29:33.036 A:start
values, so that you
don't miss an update.

00:29:33.786 --> 00:29:36.776 A:start
And when that notification
fires,

00:29:37.126 --> 00:29:39.046 A:start
what this app will do
is it will call this

00:29:39.046 --> 00:29:40.656 A:start
readDefaultsValues method.

00:29:42.016 --> 00:29:45.076 A:start
And once that's done, I actually
call the read defaults values

00:29:45.076 --> 00:29:46.576 A:start
method to read it at least once.

00:29:48.876 --> 00:29:53.116 A:start
The readDefaultValues method
does what you probably will do

00:29:53.116 --> 00:29:55.976 A:start
if you are using a
settings bundle is to read

00:29:55.976 --> 00:29:58.476 A:start
that magic key, magic
dictionary column.apple.

00:29:58.696 --> 00:30:02.306 A:start
configuration.managed, and
then it picks apart the keys

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:29:58.696 --> 00:30:02.306 A:start
configuration.managed, and
then it picks apart the keys

00:30:02.356 --> 00:30:03.776 A:start
and the values from
that dictionary.

00:30:04.776 --> 00:30:08.666 A:start
Notice that I validate
the values here so I pick

00:30:08.666 --> 00:30:11.206 A:start
out the value under
the key serverURL,

00:30:11.906 --> 00:30:13.486 A:start
make sure it's a string first.

00:30:13.896 --> 00:30:15.336 A:start
This is not a very
string validation

00:30:15.336 --> 00:30:18.566 A:start
but it's some kind validation
before accepting the URL.

00:30:19.746 --> 00:30:22.126 A:start
If a URL is not found
in the dictionary,

00:30:22.356 --> 00:30:24.226 A:start
make sure you provide
a default value

00:30:24.226 --> 00:30:25.856 A:start
that is sensible
even if it's nil.

00:30:26.466 --> 00:30:29.016 A:start
So, if that's not
available, set it to something

00:30:29.306 --> 00:30:30.836 A:start
that is reasonable default.

00:30:32.976 --> 00:30:36.936 A:start
So, for the feedback
part, what I've--

00:30:36.976 --> 00:30:41.476 A:start
what we've done here is to have
a little feedback-writing piece

00:30:41.476 --> 00:30:44.976 A:start
of code inside the increment
success and failures.

00:30:45.606 --> 00:30:48.286 A:start
So, every time the success and
failure count is incremented,

00:30:48.906 --> 00:30:52.196 A:start
we create-- we try to read
the feedback dictionary

00:30:52.196 --> 00:30:53.206 A:start
that already exists.

00:30:53.426 --> 00:30:56.226 A:start
If one doesn't exist, we create
one, a mutable dictionary

00:30:56.986 --> 00:31:01.256 A:start
under that magic key
com.apple.feedback.managed.

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:30:56.986 --> 00:31:01.256 A:start
under that magic key
com.apple.feedback.managed.

00:31:01.836 --> 00:31:06.346 A:start
We then write the value of the
success count as a key under--

00:31:06.346 --> 00:31:08.706 A:start
into this dictionary
under a well-known key.

00:31:08.706 --> 00:31:11.506 A:start
In this case, successCount,
and that's it.

00:31:11.506 --> 00:31:13.356 A:start
We just write it back
to NSUserDefaults

00:31:13.676 --> 00:31:16.316 A:start
and it just sits there until
the MDM Server picks it up.

00:31:16.906 --> 00:31:17.636 A:start
It's really simple.

00:31:19.466 --> 00:31:22.246 A:start
So, what can you use
app configuration for?

00:31:23.556 --> 00:31:25.696 A:start
Well, settings and
preferences of course.

00:31:26.346 --> 00:31:29.346 A:start
You can set your app UI settings
from here, the same kind

00:31:29.346 --> 00:31:31.526 A:start
of things that you would
set in your settings bundle

00:31:32.336 --> 00:31:35.236 A:start
but very useful thing
to setup here: URLs.

00:31:35.426 --> 00:31:39.376 A:start
URLs are very, very
powerful things to configure

00:31:39.376 --> 00:31:40.956 A:start
with the server and
you can bootstrap a lot

00:31:40.956 --> 00:31:42.076 A:start
of things using URLs.

00:31:42.956 --> 00:31:45.886 A:start
And here is where you put
the disable iCloud document

00:31:45.886 --> 00:31:46.576 A:start
sync switch.

00:31:47.206 --> 00:31:50.206 A:start
So, this allows you to
disable iCloud document sync

00:31:50.206 --> 00:31:52.086 A:start
in an enterprise
deployment situation

00:31:52.256 --> 00:31:55.256 A:start
without exposing
a user facing UI.

00:31:57.816 --> 00:32:01.956 A:start
Some things to note about this
configuration, it is stored

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:31:57.816 --> 00:32:01.956 A:start
Some things to note about this
configuration, it is stored

00:32:01.956 --> 00:32:04.266 A:start
as file protection
none just as the rest

00:32:04.266 --> 00:32:05.676 A:start
of your NSUserDefaults are.

00:32:06.596 --> 00:32:09.226 A:start
So, no passwords or
private keys please.

00:32:09.736 --> 00:32:13.686 A:start
You need to document your
dictionary keys, of course,

00:32:13.796 --> 00:32:16.696 A:start
so that the enterprise
can configure your app.

00:32:17.256 --> 00:32:19.576 A:start
And specify what
kind of data types

00:32:19.576 --> 00:32:24.066 A:start
and the valid value
ranges that you accept.

00:32:24.066 --> 00:32:27.876 A:start
And validate all the types
and values that you get.

00:32:27.876 --> 00:32:29.446 A:start
From your app's perspective,

00:32:29.726 --> 00:32:31.976 A:start
the enterprise server is
an unknown third party.

00:32:31.976 --> 00:32:33.746 A:start
They are giving you
a dictionary that--

00:32:33.746 --> 00:32:35.156 A:start
that your app is
supposed to ingest,

00:32:35.416 --> 00:32:37.286 A:start
make sure you validate
the content.

00:32:37.766 --> 00:32:42.566 A:start
And of course, keep it small,
as anything that you put

00:32:42.566 --> 00:32:44.026 A:start
in your NSUserDefaults.

00:32:44.786 --> 00:32:48.096 A:start
You're going to read your user
defaults every time your app

00:32:48.096 --> 00:32:50.726 A:start
starts up and every time it
changes so keep it small.

00:32:50.726 --> 00:32:53.986 A:start
No documents or images or little
sound files or things like that

00:32:53.986 --> 00:32:58.156 A:start
in there, put the URLs in
there and read the assets

00:32:58.156 --> 00:32:59.736 A:start
when your app starts up.

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:33:00.956 --> 00:33:03.756 A:start
Once again, a reminder,
your app may not be running

00:33:03.756 --> 00:33:05.136 A:start
so read this every time.

00:33:06.496 --> 00:33:09.136 A:start
For feedback, what's
useful to put in there?

00:33:09.746 --> 00:33:12.846 A:start
As you saw, errors and user
statistics are very useful.

00:33:13.566 --> 00:33:17.436 A:start
Again, if your app can't talk
to the server, they can't report

00:33:17.436 --> 00:33:20.076 A:start
that they can't talk with the
server so this is a good place

00:33:20.076 --> 00:33:21.466 A:start
to put that information in.

00:33:21.466 --> 00:33:24.436 A:start
So I, you know, I can't reach
that URL, here is an error.

00:33:25.446 --> 00:33:27.096 A:start
Aggregate your reports.

00:33:27.366 --> 00:33:30.416 A:start
Do not log, because it will
grow without bound and again,

00:33:30.416 --> 00:33:32.156 A:start
this belongs in your
NSUserDefaults

00:33:32.156 --> 00:33:33.876 A:start
and it needs to be small.

00:33:34.736 --> 00:33:38.856 A:start
Document your dictionary keys so
that the enterprise knows what

00:33:38.856 --> 00:33:41.246 A:start
to look for and keep it small.

00:33:41.246 --> 00:33:43.276 A:start
It goes into the same
place that your--

00:33:43.276 --> 00:33:46.796 A:start
all the rest of your defaults
go in your NSUserDefaults.

00:33:47.676 --> 00:33:50.546 A:start
Your app might not be running
when the feedback is retrieved

00:33:50.546 --> 00:33:54.456 A:start
and very importantly,
respect your user's privacy.

00:33:55.066 --> 00:33:56.126 A:start
Before you send

00:33:56.126 --> 00:33:58.416 A:start
up any personally
identifiable information,

00:33:59.106 --> 00:34:02.116 A:start
things like location,
things like that,

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:33:59.106 --> 00:34:02.116 A:start
things like location,
things like that,

00:34:02.116 --> 00:34:05.546 A:start
be sure that you are legally
allowed to do this and,

00:34:05.546 --> 00:34:09.466 A:start
of course, respect what the
user expects your app to report

00:34:09.795 --> 00:34:12.106 A:start
and preserve the user privacy.

00:34:12.335 --> 00:34:14.235 A:start
Your users will thank
you for that.

00:34:15.866 --> 00:34:19.516 A:start
For IT Integrators,
app configuration

00:34:19.516 --> 00:34:22.085 A:start
and feedback amounts to a
couple of new MDM commands

00:34:22.565 --> 00:34:27.606 A:start
so what you need to do
is to use these commands

00:34:27.606 --> 00:34:31.906 A:start
to configure your user's
devices as early as possible.

00:34:32.755 --> 00:34:35.916 A:start
So, there is an extension
to the app install command

00:34:36.116 --> 00:34:39.156 A:start
that allows you to add a
configuration dictionary inside

00:34:39.156 --> 00:34:40.536 A:start
the app installation request.

00:34:41.386 --> 00:34:44.856 A:start
So, do that if possible so that
the first time the user taps

00:34:44.856 --> 00:34:46.686 A:start
on the app, it's
already preconfigured.

00:34:47.396 --> 00:34:49.726 A:start
You can, of course,
refresh the configuration

00:34:49.726 --> 00:34:51.176 A:start
as on an ongoing basis.

00:34:52.196 --> 00:34:55.416 A:start
And use the feedback service
to detect configuration errors.

00:34:56.726 --> 00:34:58.746 A:start
All right, so that's app
configuration and feedback.

00:34:59.926 --> 00:35:02.466 A:start
Next, fonts.

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:34:59.926 --> 00:35:02.466 A:start
Next, fonts.

00:35:03.286 --> 00:35:05.386 A:start
We can now install
fonts in iOS 7,

00:35:06.266 --> 00:35:08.116 A:start
they are installed using
configuration profiles.

00:35:09.416 --> 00:35:11.166 A:start
So as an app developer,

00:35:11.456 --> 00:35:14.006 A:start
this means that the
font list may change

00:35:14.006 --> 00:35:16.536 A:start
as your app is running
and you need to listen

00:35:16.536 --> 00:35:19.886 A:start
to this notification
to detect that event.

00:35:20.766 --> 00:35:24.806 A:start
And of course, this also means
that your app may have to deal

00:35:24.806 --> 00:35:28.076 A:start
with missing fonts, et cetera,
all that fun stuff that comes

00:35:28.076 --> 00:35:30.256 A:start
with a system that
has installable fonts.

00:35:31.286 --> 00:35:34.236 A:start
One of the things about
fonts in the enterprise is

00:35:34.236 --> 00:35:37.596 A:start
that you are very likely
to encounter custom fonts

00:35:37.686 --> 00:35:41.476 A:start
in an enterprise because an
enterprise will probably have a

00:35:41.476 --> 00:35:43.566 A:start
corporate identity
font of some sort

00:35:43.566 --> 00:35:46.426 A:start
that they will install
in every device.

00:35:46.786 --> 00:35:49.146 A:start
So, your app needs to
be able to adopt to that

00:35:49.146 --> 00:35:51.736 A:start
and at least use the fonts
that are installed to--

00:35:51.736 --> 00:35:54.286 A:start
in your documents and et cetera.

00:35:55.126 --> 00:35:55.936 A:start
So, that's fonts.

00:35:56.066 --> 00:35:59.796 A:start
Next, I want to highlight a
feature that is very popular

00:35:59.796 --> 00:36:01.646 A:start
in certain industries
in the enterprise

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:35:59.796 --> 00:36:01.646 A:start
in certain industries
in the enterprise

00:36:02.176 --> 00:36:05.006 A:start
and that's single app mode.

00:36:05.136 --> 00:36:09.966 A:start
So, you may not know this, but
MDM can put certain devices

00:36:10.246 --> 00:36:12.696 A:start
into Single App Mode which means

00:36:12.696 --> 00:36:15.226 A:start
that the device will run
one app and one app only.

00:36:16.276 --> 00:36:20.426 A:start
This mode is very resilient
you can restart the device

00:36:20.426 --> 00:36:21.636 A:start
and it would launch that app.

00:36:22.016 --> 00:36:24.086 A:start
The app can crash and it
will just keep launching

00:36:24.086 --> 00:36:26.406 A:start
and just keep launching
and crash again

00:36:27.966 --> 00:36:29.196 A:start
which is a good thing.

00:36:29.246 --> 00:36:32.396 A:start
You want this behavior
because this makes it perfect

00:36:32.396 --> 00:36:38.666 A:start
for Kiosks, for point of sale
like this, for exam taking,

00:36:38.666 --> 00:36:42.406 A:start
for example, or a whole host
of different applications.

00:36:43.206 --> 00:36:46.396 A:start
So, this already an
iOS but new in iOS 7,

00:36:46.836 --> 00:36:50.246 A:start
were adding an app-requested
single app mode.

00:36:51.486 --> 00:36:54.266 A:start
So, what's this?

00:36:54.696 --> 00:36:57.236 A:start
Some of you already
know what this is.

00:36:58.356 --> 00:37:02.556 A:start
So, app-requested single app
mode allows an MDM Server

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:36:58.356 --> 00:37:02.556 A:start
So, app-requested single app
mode allows an MDM Server

00:37:02.556 --> 00:37:05.206 A:start
to pre-authorize a
set of app bundle IDs

00:37:05.206 --> 00:37:06.706 A:start
to go into single app mode.

00:37:07.296 --> 00:37:12.406 A:start
So-- and all the app has
to do is to call this API,

00:37:12.686 --> 00:37:14.136 A:start
so that first one
you see up there,

00:37:14.416 --> 00:37:17.956 A:start
UI accessibility request
guided access session

00:37:17.956 --> 00:37:20.836 A:start
that there is the parameter
you can put in there to say yes

00:37:20.836 --> 00:37:22.846 A:start
or no and enter a
session or exit a session.

00:37:23.696 --> 00:37:26.016 A:start
If successful, your
app will be locked

00:37:26.016 --> 00:37:28.096 A:start
into a single app
mode, all right?

00:37:28.396 --> 00:37:30.256 A:start
And when your app
is done with it,

00:37:30.256 --> 00:37:33.656 A:start
they can call the same API
again to get out with the--

00:37:33.656 --> 00:37:34.606 A:start
with the Boolean false.

00:37:35.406 --> 00:37:38.496 A:start
This is great for,
for example, exams.

00:37:38.746 --> 00:37:41.556 A:start
So, you have an exam
app, examination starts,

00:37:41.556 --> 00:37:43.566 A:start
the new student logs
in, you got locked in,

00:37:44.146 --> 00:37:45.716 A:start
and the exam is over,
it locks out.

00:37:46.666 --> 00:37:51.196 A:start
You can use the second API up
there, is guided access enabled,

00:37:51.776 --> 00:37:54.096 A:start
to detect whether your
app is in this mode.

00:37:54.596 --> 00:37:56.566 A:start
And you can use a notification

00:37:56.566 --> 00:37:59.626 A:start
to detect transitions
between states.

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:38:00.806 --> 00:38:04.756 A:start
So again, this state is very
resilient, your app will get--

00:38:05.326 --> 00:38:07.836 A:start
the device will only run
your app until you exit.

00:38:08.176 --> 00:38:10.316 A:start
So, make sure you have
an escape strategy

00:38:10.696 --> 00:38:13.556 A:start
in case your app crashes or
the user powers down the device

00:38:13.556 --> 00:38:14.566 A:start
and starts back up again.

00:38:15.106 --> 00:38:16.746 A:start
Try not to lock the user

00:38:16.746 --> 00:38:19.346 A:start
into your app forever,
but exit gracefully.

00:38:19.916 --> 00:38:22.956 A:start
OK. So, that's single app mode.

00:38:24.196 --> 00:38:27.986 A:start
Next up, app revocation.

00:38:28.676 --> 00:38:39.406 A:start
In iOS 7 and OS X Mavericks,
we are supporting a new model

00:38:39.406 --> 00:38:42.506 A:start
of volume purchasing
based on app assignment.

00:38:43.856 --> 00:38:47.166 A:start
If you're not aware of this,
it allows an enterprise

00:38:47.166 --> 00:38:49.126 A:start
to purchase an app
license essentially,

00:38:49.666 --> 00:38:53.876 A:start
assign it to a user's device
or a user on a iOS device

00:38:53.876 --> 00:38:56.436 A:start
and then later, revoke
that license from that--

00:38:56.436 --> 00:38:58.496 A:start
from that user and assign
it to some other user.

00:38:59.736 --> 00:39:04.316 A:start
So, what happens is your
app may be installed

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:38:59.736 --> 00:39:04.316 A:start
So, what happens is your
app may be installed

00:39:04.316 --> 00:39:07.726 A:start
on some user's device and
then, the right to run

00:39:07.726 --> 00:39:09.926 A:start
that app may be revoked
from that device.

00:39:10.066 --> 00:39:11.436 A:start
So, what happens then?

00:39:12.266 --> 00:39:16.596 A:start
When that happens, your app
license "is going to expire."

00:39:17.376 --> 00:39:21.016 A:start
The iOS-- iOS will run the app.

00:39:21.016 --> 00:39:22.806 A:start
Well, first of all,
iOS will tell the user

00:39:22.806 --> 00:39:26.216 A:start
that that app has been revoked
and give them the opportunity

00:39:26.216 --> 00:39:27.716 A:start
to buy the app from
the app store.

00:39:28.836 --> 00:39:33.006 A:start
And it will continue to
run that app for 30 days.

00:39:33.926 --> 00:39:37.176 A:start
At the end of the 30 days, iOS
will no longer launch your app

00:39:37.936 --> 00:39:40.336 A:start
but instead, will launch
an alert or show an alert

00:39:40.336 --> 00:39:41.736 A:start
that says you got
to buy this app

00:39:41.736 --> 00:39:43.526 A:start
from the App Store
to continue using it.

00:39:44.106 --> 00:39:46.476 A:start
The reason we give the
grace period there is

00:39:46.476 --> 00:39:48.166 A:start
so that the user
doesn't lose their data

00:39:48.166 --> 00:39:50.806 A:start
and to give them an opportunity
to buy from the app store.

00:39:51.186 --> 00:39:55.926 A:start
If you're checking for receipts
already, the expiry date is

00:39:55.926 --> 00:39:58.296 A:start
on the receipt, so you might
want to check with that too.

00:39:58.596 --> 00:39:59.976 A:start
There is the session on
the receipt checking,

00:39:59.976 --> 00:40:02.596 A:start
I recommend it-- I
recommended you go to that one

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:39:59.976 --> 00:40:02.596 A:start
I recommend it-- I
recommended you go to that one

00:40:02.596 --> 00:40:05.556 A:start
and we'll cite that at the
end of the presentation.

00:40:06.096 --> 00:40:09.836 A:start
So, that's management.

00:40:12.446 --> 00:40:18.186 A:start
So, as you can see, iOS 7
brings a lot to the table in all

00:40:18.186 --> 00:40:21.476 A:start
of these fields and there's
a lot that you can do,

00:40:21.746 --> 00:40:23.856 A:start
with very little
effort in some cases,

00:40:24.196 --> 00:40:26.366 A:start
to extend you app just
a little bit more,

00:40:27.046 --> 00:40:29.526 A:start
to make it very attractive
to the enterprise.

00:40:30.886 --> 00:40:36.436 A:start
Now, I want to talk a bit about
the philosophy that we have

00:40:36.436 --> 00:40:40.126 A:start
on iOS about enterprise apps.

00:40:40.896 --> 00:40:46.166 A:start
There are many cases where
an app developer who wants

00:40:46.166 --> 00:40:48.426 A:start
to put their app into
the enterprise just wants

00:40:48.426 --> 00:40:49.836 A:start
to tag something on in the end.

00:40:50.086 --> 00:40:51.796 A:start
I'm just going to wrap
my app in something,

00:40:51.796 --> 00:40:54.226 A:start
I'm going to add some
library to it and it's going

00:40:54.226 --> 00:40:54.996 A:start
to make it all better.

00:40:55.366 --> 00:40:58.396 A:start
It's going to make it
secure and stuff like that.

00:40:58.576 --> 00:41:05.726 A:start
And we don't-- we encourage
you to do something different,

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:40:58.576 --> 00:41:05.726 A:start
And we don't-- we encourage
you to do something different,

00:41:07.396 --> 00:41:11.966 A:start
we encourage you to
build the next generation

00:41:12.516 --> 00:41:15.096 A:start
of enterprise apps, right?

00:41:15.516 --> 00:41:22.196 A:start
And what that means is we
would like you to build this--

00:41:22.196 --> 00:41:24.236 A:start
the iOS features into your app.

00:41:24.556 --> 00:41:26.876 A:start
The iOS 7 features,
they are like, you know,

00:41:26.876 --> 00:41:32.716 A:start
a Single Sign On, data
protection, Managed Open In,

00:41:34.096 --> 00:41:36.476 A:start
configuration or feedback for
app developers, of course.

00:41:37.056 --> 00:41:41.836 A:start
Build this right into your
app so that as iOS grows

00:41:42.146 --> 00:41:45.606 A:start
and additional features are
added, your app is ready to go

00:41:45.606 --> 00:41:50.146 A:start
into the enterprise,
to grow along with it.

00:41:50.686 --> 00:41:53.716 A:start
IT Integrators, I encourage
you to look for apps

00:41:53.716 --> 00:41:57.396 A:start
that actually support these
iOS 7 features inside their app

00:41:57.676 --> 00:42:00.036 A:start
natively and not just
tacked on at the end.

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:41:57.676 --> 00:42:00.036 A:start
natively and not just
tacked on at the end.

00:42:00.546 --> 00:42:02.236 A:start
These are the apps
that are going

00:42:02.236 --> 00:42:05.766 A:start
to serve your enterprise very
well into the next decade.

00:42:06.286 --> 00:42:17.186 A:start
So, to sum up, if you
ask me, you know Dave,

00:42:17.186 --> 00:42:20.976 A:start
as an app developer, what three
things can I add or do to my app

00:42:21.606 --> 00:42:24.446 A:start
to make it that much more
attractive to the enterprise.

00:42:25.736 --> 00:42:27.356 A:start
I will say these three things.

00:42:27.866 --> 00:42:32.536 A:start
First, support app
configuration and feedback.

00:42:33.146 --> 00:42:35.956 A:start
It's a very light-weight
extension to your app

00:42:36.486 --> 00:42:40.426 A:start
that will greatly help
the IT Integrators

00:42:40.886 --> 00:42:42.766 A:start
to deploy your app correctly

00:42:43.196 --> 00:42:45.956 A:start
and to save them a
lot of support calls.

00:42:48.036 --> 00:42:52.596 A:start
Next, use NSURLConnection
and NSURLSession.

00:42:52.806 --> 00:42:57.206 A:start
These are your best bets to
get an app into the enterprise

00:42:57.206 --> 00:43:02.416 A:start
and have it work correctly
the first time, all right?

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:42:57.206 --> 00:43:02.416 A:start
and have it work correctly
the first time, all right?

00:43:02.416 --> 00:43:03.606 A:start
I know in some cases, you can't,

00:43:04.136 --> 00:43:07.356 A:start
but if you can, please
do use that.

00:43:07.356 --> 00:43:12.376 A:start
And finally, build in data
protection and security

00:43:12.736 --> 00:43:15.026 A:start
into your app, don't leave
it as an afterthought.

00:43:16.216 --> 00:43:18.136 A:start
When you write files to
disk, consider what kind

00:43:18.136 --> 00:43:19.716 A:start
of data protection
you're going to use.

00:43:20.006 --> 00:43:21.816 A:start
When you write items
into the keychain,

00:43:22.626 --> 00:43:25.816 A:start
think about what the use cases
might be in the enterprise.

